<DOC><DOCNO> AP880909-0215 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-88 2007EDT</FILEID><FIRST>s i BC-NorthAfrica-Glance ADV18   09-09 0375</FIRST><SECOND>BC-North Africa-Glance, ADV 18,0380</SECOND><NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 18, and Thereafter</NOTE><HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: North Africa _ Facts and Figures</HEAD><HEAD>With BC-North Africa</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here are some facts and figures on the Maghreb in North Africa:   THE COUNTRIES AND THE LAND _ Algeria, Morocco, Tunisia, Libyaand Mauritania make up the Maghreb, or the Arab West, in NorthAfrica. They cover about 2,341,000 square miles, one-fifth of theAfrican continent. This is about two-thirds the area of thecontinental United States.</TEXT><TEXT>   THE PEOPLE _ The total population is about 68 million and 99percent are Moslems. Virtually all speak one of several dialects ofArabic. Most are descendants of the Berber tribes who were theoriginal inhabitants before the arrival of the Arabs. Most of thepeople are farmers and herders. Most of the population isconcentrated around the main cities, Casablanca, Marrakech,Algiers, Oran, Constantine, Tunis and Tripoli.</TEXT><TEXT>   THE ECONOMY _ Algeria, Libya and Tunisia have economies based onexports of oil and gas. Tunisia also has a substantial income fromtourism and from the export of wine and citrus fruit. Tourism, wineand citrus fruit also are important in Morocco, but the largestearner of foreign currency is the export of phosphates, worth about$400 million in 1986. Mauritania mines about 10 million tons ofiron ore annually at the Zouerate mines, and catches 35,000 tons offish _ one-tenth of the total in Mauritanian waters. Currencies andtheir equivalents in U.S. money: Algerian dinar (17 cents),Moroccan dirham (13 cents), Tunisian dinar ($1.30), Libyan dinar(30 cents), Mauritanian ouguiya (2 cents).</TEXT><TEXT>   HISTORY _ Christianized under the Roman Empire, the area becamepart of the Islamic world in the eighth century. In the 19thcentury, it came under French, Spanish and Italian colonization. Onindependence after World War II, the area came mostly undertotalitarian or absolutist regimes. Morocco and Algeria fought abrief border war in 1963, followed by a long quarrel over theWestern Sahara. Tunisia and Libya quarrelled over citizens' rightsand over oil prospecting in the Mediterranean. Algeria and Libyahave a long-pending territorial dispute. In May, they began work ona framework for a Confederation.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv Sunday, Sept. 18</NOTE></DOC>